title: For Sale:  Scam warning:  guy trying to sell Springfield 1911 Loaded model
postcontent:
He claims it is the Loaded model and wants $775 for it.

However...

This pics he posted are of a MilSpec model.  It is easy to tell given the combat sights, the standard beavertail (the Loaded has fixed night sights and a pronounced beavertail), and the non-ambidextrous safety.

This is also not a new Loaded since the case for the newer ones is the larger black case that looks like a XDm case.  I know.  I bought a new Loaded model (PX9109LP) in 2013.

Posted as a community service to others on this forum.  Watch out for scams.

PS:  There are other 1911 MilSpec ads on here that seem to be legitimate.  I am only warning about the one advertising as a 1911 Loaded, in the Vancouver WA area, and for about $775.

Make me offer! Description of type of ammo below!! Open to trades 

45 black tip
Armor Piercing: Identified by a black tip, this general purpose armor piercing bullet uses a core of very dense, hardened tungsten steel. Contrary to common belief, it is not the best armor piercing 50 BMG round, but it is the best general purpose armor piercing round. Bullet weights are in the 690 grain to 705 grain range depending on year, model, and country of origin. Covered in a copper jacket, this round can be found with either a lead plug base or with the jacked swagged at its base for the gas seal. This is a boat tailed projectile.
16 silver tip
Armor Piercing Incendiary: Identified with a silver or aluminum colored tip (not to be confused with the pointy Hornady AMAX match round which uses a real aluminum tip). This is generally the best common armor piercing round. Used where fear of secondary ignition effect after piercing is wanted or not a problem. The round is similar to the armor piercing round in that it has a dense hardened tungsten steel core but slightly shorter, allowing a incendiary compound to be enclosed in front of it under the boat tailed copper jacket sealed with a lead gas plug at the rear.

title: For Sale/Trade:  900 Rounds Federal HST .40S&W JHP*PRICE DROP*
postcontent:
$31.94 PER BOX! Priced lower than anywhere else online I can find. 

For sale/trade is 900 rounds of Federal HST 155gr JHP for a .40S&W. I am asking far less than retail for cash offers.

It's easy to find the much less desirable Hydra-Shok ammunition on the shelf, and many people are intrigued by the "post" inside the hollow point. If you do the research, and I suggest you do, you will find that HST is extremely tough to beat.

That's why HST has almost never (in my experience) been for sale on the shelves at your local gun shop - I have only ever found it online, for a premium price, and in small or limited quantities. I have recently switched to a different caliber for my preferred CCW and cannot find anywhere that sells HST in bulk, must less a place with a single box in stock right now.
I live in Puyallup, but will be willing to drive a reasonable distance to meet - or even ship if you want to pay for shipping.

Take a look here for FBI Protocol test results on this ammunition
http://le.atk.com/ammunition/federal/handgun/details.aspx?id=567

This is a Crosman Pumpmaster 760 air RIFLE.
I capitalize rifle, because this is the only year I know of that the barrel of this model was rifled.
Mfg. in July of 1989, this air rifle was bought by my father and handed down to me.
(I was born in 88)

It's never fired a BB, and the rifling is in great condition.
It's been properly maintained, and for a 24 year old air rifle it's in top condition.

It does have his name engraved into it and could use a reblue, so it's no collectors piece.
But it is a great example of history, and how things used to be better made.

$40 OBO.

I see smooth bore 760s at gander mountain for $50, which seems way too high.
So just make me an offer.
